prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band6_(ch3oh+hcn)
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
This is our primary Science configuration. However, we kindly request to observe these Science Goals back-to-back.
We have identified a CH3OH setting that can target several emission lines along with the HCN(3-2) emission line (Table 1). In particular, methanol is considered a good thermometer in the coma, having multiple strong rotational bands throughout the mm/sub-mm, and its observation is essential to obtain the overall 'picture' of excitation conditions in the coma. A rotation diagram for each coma point (coupled with the retrieved velocity profiles) will provide a 3D distribution map of temperatures and enable unique interpretation of the molecular distributions in the coma.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We request four correlator settings to cover the primary lines of interest in Band 6 (CH3OH and HCN). Basebands 1 and 2 (USB) will target multiple CH3OH lines and HCN (3-2), while Basebands 3 and 4 (LSB) aim to sample CH3OH lines. All baselines have the same spectral resolution, and Baseband 1 and 2 overlap to provide appropiate sampling of all lines. We also seek to cross-check the calibration (line amplitude) between correlators B1 and B2.

We propose observations during November 2015, when ALMA will be using the C36-7 antenna configuration (see Table 3 in the ALMA Cycle 3 Proposers Guide and Capabilities handbook). During this period, ALMA will provide spatial resolution of 0.05" (or, ~60 km at 1.8 AU distance to the comet) and will permit mapping temperatures up to nucleocentric distances of ~500 km in Band 6. This will allow us to sense the excitation conditions in the inner coma. Such angular resolution can provide spatial 3D snapshots of the coma at multiple points within the ALMA's FOV, and thus yield information on the gas kinematics. The latter represents unique information, and our custom algorithms can help decipher the observed gas behavior.

Our goal is to explore the gas release of the target molecules near the nucleus and obtain accurate 3D maps of rotational temperatures. According to our estimates, based on realistic observing conditions and gas productivity of comet US10 (Catalina), parent volatiles can be successfully detected in Band 6 (see Table 1). An RMS noise level of 10 K is required in order to detect these molecules at S/N ~ 3 (or better) in our survey. This will allow us to map these molecules with sufficient signal-to-noise and measure their spatial distributions in the inner coma.

The data rate is needed to properly sample multiple emission lines of each molecular species. The high sensitivity and spectral resolving power provided uniquely by ALMA are critical for this investigation.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band3_(ch3oh+hcn)
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
This is our secondary Science configuration. However, we kindly request to observe these Science Goals back-to-back.
We have identified an alternative CH3OH setting that can target several emission lines along with the HCN(1-0) emission line (Table 1). The aim of this configuration is to obtain a sensitive test of the hyperfine HCN (1-0) and HCN (3-2) lines in the coma (almost simultaneously) and test common excitation conditions and temperatures compared to the CH3OH lines.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We request three correlator settings to cover the primary lines of interest in Band 3 (CH3OH and HCN). Baseband 1 (LSB) aims to sample the hyperfine HCN lines, while Basebands 2 (LSB) and 3 (USB) will target CH3OH lines. The larger spectral resolution in Baseband 3 is required to sample multiple (CH3OH) emission lines in the vecinity of the targeted methanol line.

We propose observations during November 2015, when ALMA will be using the C36-7 antenna configuration (see Table 3 in the ALMA Cycle 3 Proposers Guide and Capabilities handbook). During this period, ALMA will provide spatial resolution of 0.1" (or, ~130 km at 1.8 AU distance to the comet) and will permit mapping temperatures up to nucleocentric distances of ~1500 km in Band 3. The different angular resolutions and scales, compared to those of Band 6, will permit to probe different regions in the cometary coma. Such angular resolution can provide spatial 3D snapshots of the coma at multiple points within the ALMAs FOV, and thus yield information on the gas kinematics. The latter represents unique information, and our custom algorithms can help decipher the observed gas behavior.

Our goal is to explore the gas release of the target molecules near the nucleus and obtain accurate 3D maps of rotational temperatures. According to our estimates, based on realistic observing conditions and gas productivity of comet US10 (Catalina), parent volatiles can be successfully detected in Band 3 (see Table 1). An RMS noise level of 30 K is required in order to detect these molecules at S/N ~ 3 for the weaker lines, but significantly larger for other lines in our survey. This will allow us to map these species with sufficient signal-to-noise andto measure their spatial distributions in the inner coma.

The data rate is needed to properly sample multiple emission lines of each molecular species. The high sensitivity and spectral resolving power provided uniquely by ALMA are critical for this investigation.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: A vast variety of coma models predict steep gradients in the temperature distribution near the cometary nucleus. Yet astronomical observatories have not been able to prove this long-standing prediction. Today, ALMA is the sole facility capable to test these properties. During Cycle 3, the extended ALMA configuration will allow the unique opportunity to sense small-scale details in the inner coma. We propose to obtain high sensitivity 3D temperature maps of key species in comet C/2013 US10 (Catalina). Our proposed observations will go beyond our current studies of temperature distribution in the coma thanks to the improved angular resolution. IR observations will yield complementary information like production rates of primary volatiles, including water, methanol and hydrogen cyanide, along with complementary 1D maps. Considering the projected production rates in comet US10, the level of detail and expected sensitivity of these maps will yield unprecedented details of the nucleus vicinity. This will highly impact our current understanding of the inner coma and aid the local measurements of comet 67P by Rosetta.
